<quantity box="[851,941,904,930]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="33" pageNumber="43" unit="mm" value="32.0">32 mm</quantity>
conch diameter in haematitic ironstone (
<figureCitation box="[237,340,939,965]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="33.[227,270,1857,1883]" captionTargetBox="[281,1380,1582,1819]" captionTargetId="figure-336@33.[281,1381,1582,1819]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Fig. 21. Acanthoclymeniaplanorbis (Sandberger &amp; Sandberger, 1851).A. Lectotype 46a in theWiesbaden collection from Oberscheld; photograph and reproduction of the figure of Sandberger &amp; Sandberger (1850–1856: pl. 9 fig. 3a). B. Paratype 46b in the Wiesbaden collection from Oberscheld; photograph and reproduction of the figure of Sandberger &amp; Sandberger (1850–1856: pl. 9 fig. 3). C. Probably lost specimen; photograph and reproduction of the figure of Sandberger &amp; Sandberger (1850–1856: pl. 9 fig. 3d, e). Scale bar units = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6629171" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6629171/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="43">Fig. 21A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[227,1436,1004,1066]" pageId="33" pageNumber="43">
<typeStatus box="[227,387,1004,1030]" pageId="33" pageNumber="43">Paralectotype</typeStatus>
Wiesb. 46b: incomplete specimen with 
<quantity box="[873,959,1004,1031]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="33" pageNumber="43" unit="mm" value="22.0">22 mm</quantity>
conch diameter in haematitic ironstone (
<figureCitation box="[237,340,1039,1065]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="33.[227,270,1857,1883]" captionTargetBox="[281,1380,1582,1819]" captionTargetId="figure-336@33.[281,1381,1582,1819]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Fig. 21. Acanthoclymeniaplanorbis (Sandberger &amp; Sandberger, 1851).A. Lectotype 46a in theWiesbaden collection from Oberscheld; photograph and reproduction of the figure of Sandberger &amp; Sandberger (1850–1856: pl. 9 fig. 3a). B. Paratype 46b in the Wiesbaden collection from Oberscheld; photograph and reproduction of the figure of Sandberger &amp; Sandberger (1850–1856: pl. 9 fig. 3). C. Probably lost specimen; photograph and reproduction of the figure of Sandberger &amp; Sandberger (1850–1856: pl. 9 fig. 3d, e). Scale bar units = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6629171" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6629171/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="43">Fig. 21B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[226,1436,1105,1167]" pageId="33" pageNumber="43">
MB.C.30438: slab and counterslab with 
<specimenCount box="[697,869,1105,1131]" pageId="33" pageNumber="43" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
(13 and 
<quantity box="[970,1037,1105,1131]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="33" pageNumber="43" unit="mm" value="7.0">7 mm</quantity>
conch diameter) co-occuring with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Holzapfel" baseAuthorityYear="1882" box="[226,496,1140,1166]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Beloceratidae" genus="Mesobeloceras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ammonoidea" pageId="33" pageNumber="43" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="kayseri">
<emphasis box="[226,496,1140,1166]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="43">Mesobeloceras kayseri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in haematite ore (
<figureCitation box="[710,814,1140,1166]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="34.[227,270,765,791]" captionTargetBox="[529,1131,302,723]" captionTargetId="figure-348@34.[529,1134,302,725]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="Fig. 22. Acanthoclymenia planorbis (Sandberger &amp; Sandberger, 1851). A. Specimen MB.C.30438 (Koch Coll.) from Oberscheld. B. Specimen MB.C.30439 (Kauth Coll.) from Oberscheld (Königszug Mine). Scale bar units = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6628119" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6628119/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="43">Fig. 22A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[227,1436,1205,1267]" pageId="33" pageNumber="43">
MB.C.30439: moderately well-preserved specimen with 
<quantity box="[900,983,1206,1232]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="33" pageNumber="43" unit="mm" value="12.0">12 mm</quantity>
conch diameter in haematitic iron ore (
<figureCitation box="[237,340,1241,1267]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="34.[227,270,765,791]" captionTargetBox="[529,1131,302,723]" captionTargetId="figure-348@34.[529,1134,302,725]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="Fig. 22. Acanthoclymenia planorbis (Sandberger &amp; Sandberger, 1851). A. Specimen MB.C.30438 (Koch Coll.) from Oberscheld. B. Specimen MB.C.30439 (Kauth Coll.) from Oberscheld (Königszug Mine). Scale bar units = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6628119" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6628119/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="43">Fig. 22B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[227,1438,1306,1473]" pageId="33" pageNumber="43">
The specimens contribute only little to our knowledge of the species. All are embedded on rock slabs (
<figureCitation box="[237,329,1341,1367]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="34.[227,270,765,791]" captionTargetBox="[529,1131,302,723]" captionTargetId="figure-348@34.[529,1134,302,725]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="Fig. 22. Acanthoclymenia planorbis (Sandberger &amp; Sandberger, 1851). A. Specimen MB.C.30438 (Koch Coll.) from Oberscheld. B. Specimen MB.C.30439 (Kauth Coll.) from Oberscheld (Königszug Mine). Scale bar units = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6628119" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6628119/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="43">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
), which prevents precise measurement of the whorl width, but it is clear that the conch is extremely discoidal. It is also clear that the whorl profile is pear-shaped with a rounded umbilical wall, convex flanks, a subangular ventrolateral shoulder and a flattened venter. The umbilicus has nearly exactly half the value of the conch diameter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
